div.div:
\begin{equation*}
\begin{array}{rcl} \displaystyle \int_0^{5} (4 e^x+5 \sin x)\, dx \amp =\amp   
\displaystyle  4 e^x-5 \cos x  \Big]_0^{5}
\\ \amp =\amp  (4 e^{5} - 5 \cos 5) - (4 e^0 - 5 \cos0 ) 
\\ \amp =\amp  4 e^{5} - 5 \cos 5  + 1 
\end{array}
\end{equation*}

(a) Suppose we choose an \(x\text{,}\) \(0\leq x\leq 5\text{.}\) If \(\Delta x\) is a small fraction of a meter, then the density of the rod is approximately \(\delta(x)\) anywhere from \(x\) to \(x+\Delta x\) meters from the left end of the rod. The mass of the rod from \(x\) to \(x+\Delta x\) meters is therefore approximately \(\delta(x) \Delta x = (1 + 2 x)\Delta x\text{.}\) If we slice the rod into \(N\) pieces, then a Riemann sum is \(\Sigma_{i=1}^{N}(1 + 2 x_i)\Delta x\text{,}\) or, more loosely, \(\Sigma (1 + 2 x)\Delta x\text{.}\) (b) The definite integral is

\begin{equation*}
M=\int_0^{5} \delta(x)\,dx =
\int_0^{5} (1 + 2 x)\,dx=
(1 x + 1 x^2)\bigg|_0^{5} = 30 \hbox{ grams}.
\end{equation*}

\begin{equation*}
\frac{1}{(x+6)(x+8)}=\frac{A}{x+6}+\frac{B}{x+8},
\end{equation*}
giving

\begin{equation*}
1 =  A(x+8)+B(x+6),
\end{equation*}
or

\begin{equation*}
1 = (A+B)x+ (8 A+6 B).
\end{equation*}
Solving for \(A\) and \(B\text{,}\) we find \(A = 0.5\) and \(B = -0.5\text{,}\) so

\begin{equation*}
\int \frac{1}{(x+6)(x+8)}\,dx= \int\frac{0.5}{x+6}\,dx +
\int \frac{-0.5}{x+8}\,dx = 0.5\ln\!\left(\left|x+6\right|\right)-0.5\ln\!\left(\left|x+8\right|\right)+C.
\end{equation*}

\(\Delta y\) and radius \(x=\root 6\of{y}\text{.}\) Thus

\begin{equation*}
\hbox{Volume of slice }\approx \pi x^2\Delta y =\pi y^{1/3}\,\Delta y,
\end{equation*}
and

\begin{equation*}
\hbox{Volume of solid } = 
\lim_{\Delta y\to 0}\Sigma\pi y^{1/3}\,\Delta y
= \int_0^1 \pi y^{1/3}\, dy
\end{equation*}


\begin{equation*}
= {3 \pi\over 4} y^{1 + 1/3}\bigg|_0^1 = {3 \pi\over 4}.
\end{equation*}
